{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9e5212eb-d73b-438f-8be6-46c1bd11ae29","content":"In .NET MAUI, `Application` still has `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` — so your existing overrides will compile. However, the **recommended** approach is to use `Window` lifecycle events:\n\n```csharp\n// App.xaml.cs\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created  += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnStart */ };\n    window.Stopped  += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnSleep */ };\n    window.Resumed  += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnResume */ };\n\n    // Additional events not available in Xamarin.Forms:\n    window.Activated   += (s, e) => { };\n    window.Deactivated += (s, e) => { };\n    window.Destroying  += (s, e) => { };\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Key differences:**\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window Event | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `Created` | Fired once on launch |\n| `OnSleep()` | `Stopped` | App backgrounded |\n| `OnResume()` | `Resumed` | App foregrounded |\n| *(none)* | `Activated` / `Deactivated` | Focus gained/lost |\n\nThe `Window` approach is preferred because MAUI supports multi-window scenarios (especially on iPad/desktop), and each window gets its own lifecycle.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7c679ca5-9598-44e3-ba3a-52af0b99fb8c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` in your `Application` subclass.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed. You use the `Window` lifecycle events or the `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`. The `Application` class still exists but the recommended approach is different.\n\nActually, in .NET MAUI, `Application` still has `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` virtual methods that you can override — they were carried over. But the more modern/recommended approach is to use the `Window` lifecycle events or platform-specific lifecycle events via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`.\n\n\nThe backward-compatible approach still works, but the preferred pattern in MAUI is leveraging `Window` lifecycle methods or configuring platform-specific events through `MauiProgram.cs` for more granular control.","outputTokens":841,"requestId":"3C21:16C73:D5CE73:10A0F33:6A0129E0"},"id":"4c40ec3e-a40b-4b19-96e6-9e384427e885","timestamp":"2026-05-11T00:59:27.966Z","parentId":"16c2b18f-da81-4d00-8e76-b1960d781410"}
